You-mask, what new files get by default.

When you create a file, the kernel does not ask what permissions it should have; it applies a default, usually read-write for the owner and read-only for everyone else on a file, and read-write-execute for the owner with read-execute for others on a directory. But that default is not fixed. It is calculated from a value called the you-mask, short for user file-creation mask, and the you-mask works by subtraction: it says which permissions to remove from the maximum.

The maximum a new file is allowed is octal six-six-six, that is read and write for everyone but never execute, and for a directory the maximum is octal seven-seven-seven. The usual you-mask is octal zero-two-two, which is a set of bits to take away. Subtract zero-two-two from six-six-six and you get six-four-four, the familiar owner-can-edit, others-can-read. Subtract it from seven-seven-seven and you get seven-five-five for directories. In words, that you-mask simply removes write permission from group and other, which is why you see six-four-four and seven-five-five everywhere.

A stricter default, common on servers, is octal zero-seven-seven. That subtracts everything from group and other, so new files come out as six-zero-zero and new directories as seven-zero-zero, completely private to the owner, which is what you want when handling sensitive data. You can see your current value just by running you-mask on its own, and change it for the current shell by giving it a new number. To make the change permanent, you set it in a shell startup file. The one thing to keep straight is that the number you give is the mask itself, the bits to remove, not the result you want to end up with.
